{
  "analysis": "I need to process a video of someone playing Zork and extract the text commands they input. Let me start by examining the video file and then extracting frames to read the screen contents.",
  "plan": "First, I'll check the video file properties, then extract frames at regular intervals to capture each screen of text. I'll use ffmpeg for frame extraction and potentially OCR tools to read the text.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la /app/video.mp4\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "ffmpeg -i /app/video.mp4 2>&1 | head -30\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "which ffmpeg && which tesseract\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "ffmpeg and tesseract are not installed. I need to install them to process the video. First, I should update the package manager and install the necessary tools. Then extract frames from the video and perform OCR to read the text.",
  "plan": "1. Update apt and install ffmpeg and tesseract-ocr. 2. Extract frames from the video at regular intervals (e.g., 1 frame per second). 3. Run OCR on each frame to extract text. 4. Analyze the text to find player commands (likely the lines after a prompt like '>' or the bottom of the screen). 5. Filter and format commands into a list.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "apt-get update\n",
      "duration": 30.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "apt-get install -y ffmpeg tesseract-ocr\n",
      "duration": 60.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "mkdir -p /app/frames\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "ffmpeg -i /app/video.mp4 -vf fps=1 /app/frames/frame_%04d.png 2>&1 | tail -10\n",
      "duration": 30.0
    }
  ]
}
